00:46:25,783 --> 00:46:27,013
He's too tall!

723
00:46:29,453 --> 00:46:31,793
Which is great,
‘cause he is too tall, poor guy.

724
00:46:32,189 --> 00:46:34,529
So the kid was really
empathizing with him.

725
00:46:39,997 --> 00:46:42,167
And this is where we start to go

726
00:46:42,533 --> 00:46:45,143
into the survival montage.

727
00:46:45,569 --> 00:46:48,699
We tried so many
different types of music,

728
00:46:49,206 --> 00:46:52,666
songs that would underlie it.

729
00:46:53,744 --> 00:46:57,554
We were really stuck on it, and then
Hans decided he wanted to take a shot

730
00:46:58,149 --> 00:46:59,929
at just composing something

731
00:47:00,251 --> 00:47:03,621
and it really hits
every beat of this

732
00:47:04,155 --> 00:47:07,085
and the attitudes of the characters.
He really did a great job,

733
00:47:07,558 --> 00:47:10,188
building it to this climactic,
monumental moment

734
00:47:10,628 --> 00:47:12,088
with the Statue Of Liberty.

735
00:47:23,007 --> 00:47:24,587
It was a great idea Tom
came up with,

736
00:47:24,875 --> 00:47:28,095
that they construct their own version
of the Statue of Liberty,

737
00:47:28,612 --> 00:47:32,042
that they could use
the Liberty's torch as a beacon.

738
00:47:41,792 --> 00:47:44,452
Which led into
another storyboard artist's

739
00:47:44,895 --> 00:47:46,565
Planet Of The Apes reference,

740
00:47:48,232 --> 00:47:50,542
which kind of just seemed
to work right into this.

741
00:47:50,935 --> 00:47:55,154
We do have a lot of shameless
film references in Madagascar

742
00:47:55,806 --> 00:47:58,526
and we just think they're funny.

743
00:47:58,976 --> 00:48:01,696
And usually, though, what
we'll try to do is give it a test

744
00:48:02,146 --> 00:48:04,636
that, if it works even if you
don't get the reference,

745
00:48:05,049 --> 00:48:08,829
if it makes sense
to some degree,

746
00:48:09,420 --> 00:48:11,410
within the context, then it's OK.

747
00:48:13,290 --> 00:48:15,430
Yeah, we had him doing
the Tom Hanks bit here,

748
00:48:15,793 --> 00:48:17,963
but we just thought
it was too much Cast Away.

749
00:48:18,329 --> 00:48:21,759
So we kind of took out
the "I make fire" bit.

750
00:48:25,035 --> 00:48:27,725
- Fire is very difficult.
- In computer animation.

751
00:48:28,172 --> 00:48:32,562
This was a monumental task to do
the effects here of this right here.

752
00:48:34,378 --> 00:48:36,078
And breaking apart like this.

753
00:48:40,918 --> 00:48:43,108
We had a lot of extra material
in this sequence.

754
00:48:43,487 --> 00:48:46,387
Some of it was animated, I believe,
between Marty and Alex.

755
00:48:47,458 --> 00:48:48,688
Mireille was great.

756
00:48:48,926 --> 00:48:50,976
We had... this sequence was probably,

757
00:48:51,328 --> 00:48:51,428
you know, felt like 15 minutes.

758
00:48:51,429 --> 00:48:53,679
you know, felt like 15 minutes.

759
00:48:54,064 --> 00:48:57,163
And Mireille was really good
about saying,

760
00:48:57,668 --> 00:49:00,658
this bit's good, this bit's good,
you could really tighten it up.

761
00:49:01,138 --> 00:49:04,857
It was like pulling teeth, but we're
so glad we did tighten that sequence.

762
00:49:05,443 --> 00:49:08,073
- Thank you, Mireille.
- Mireille Soria, our producer.

763
00:49:12,483 --> 00:49:16,233
We always wanted to have this scene
in the plane, which is good,

764
00:49:16,821 --> 00:49:19,921
and the comments like maybe
the skeleton hand would be too dark.

765
00:49:20,424 --> 00:49:23,764
But we just thought it was funny,
and hopefully it ended up funny.

766
00:49:24,295 --> 00:49:27,775
So we put smiles on the skeleton's
faces so it wouldn't be...

767
00:49:28,332 --> 00:49:30,942
There's one right there.
So it wouldn't be too gruesome.

768
00:49:31,368 --> 00:49:34,268
We wanted it to be like
a little tree house kind of scene.

769
00:49:36,907 --> 00:49:40,007
It's great that the skeleton hand
sort of does the right poses.

770
00:49:44,915 --> 00:49:47,465
There's Teemo
that goes into the ball.

771
00:49:47,885 --> 00:49:50,315
l wish we had used Teemo more.

772
00:49:50,721 --> 00:49:53,441
- It's a tenrec.
- I's an actual animal,

773
00:49:53,891 --> 00:49:56,501
all these animals are,
but Teemo was funny.

774
00:49:56,927 --> 00:50:00,087
He used to have this French accent
and had a bigger role early on,

775
00:50:00,598 --> 00:50:03,058
but it was reduced to
popping into a little ball now.

776
00:50:03,501 --> 00:50:05,281
We had a bigger role for Masacoro,

777
00:50:05,603 --> 00:50:08,033
which is that chameleon
that you see occasionally.

778
00:50:09,373 --> 00:50:11,923
She was a psychic and
she would stick her tongue out

779
00:50:12,343 --> 00:50:15,942
onto people's forehead
and change colors like a mood ring.

780
00:50:16,514 --> 00:50:18,474
And she read their fortunes to them.

781
00:50:27,625 --> 00:50:29,615
Again, Sacha, just going off.

782
00:50:29,960 --> 00:50:31,710
He would go off for minutes.

783
00:50:32,029 --> 00:50:34,869
There'd be one line of dialogue
and he'd go off for ten minutes,

784
00:50:35,332 --> 00:50:37,882
having imaginary conversations
with other lemurs,

785
00:50:38,302 --> 00:50:40,232
and we'd just be in tears,
just laughing.

786
00:50:50,714 --> 00:50:53,904
Sacha, there's certain words he would
say that Julien wouldn't know,

787
00:50:54,418 --> 00:50:56,498
he's not smart enough to know,

788
00:50:56,854 --> 00:50:58,993
so he came up with a language

789
00:50:59,356 --> 00:51:01,376
tailored to someone
who wasn't so bright,

790
00:51:01,725 --> 00:51:04,245
and it added a lot to his character.

791
00:51:05,329 --> 00:51:07,549
That was the second place
we say Madagascar.

792
00:51:07,932 --> 00:51:10,482
And that's about all we wanted
to mention originally.

793
00:51:33,357 --> 00:51:36,346
So wouldn't you know,
this is one of those moments,

794
00:51:36,827 --> 00:51:40,577
Alex and Marty connect,
you know, kind of intimately.

795
00:51:41,165 --> 00:51:43,595
It felt like it was
a good point in the film.

796
00:51:46,236 --> 00:51:49,516
Hans Zimmer brings this
friendship theme back in here.

797
00:51:50,040 --> 00:51:53,000
Yeah, which really helps out
moments like this.

798
00:52:02,519 --> 00:52:06,209
This is a long shot.
The animator took a lot of time.

799
00:52:06,790 --> 00:52:08,430
Some subtle performances.

800
00:52:23,874 --> 00:52:27,564
Another story artist idea
that just kind of adds to the shot,

801
00:52:28,145 --> 00:52:30,335
that help sign falling.

802
00:52:32,149 --> 00:52:34,899
So even though they're in the wild
and Marty, you know...

803
00:52:35,352 --> 00:52:38,862
We wanted to have them
live like, you know,

804
00:52:40,224 --> 00:52:42,684
like New Yorkers
even though they're in the wild.

805
00:52:43,093 --> 00:52:46,603
So we thought it was funny
to have this apartment door scene,

806
00:52:47,898 --> 00:52:49,888
with the chains and everything.

807
00:52:50,234 --> 00:52:54,214
This kind of reuniting moment,

808
00:52:54,838 --> 00:52:57,448
and then just have a free-standing door
it was funny.

809
00:52:58,542 --> 00:53:00,852
Again the sound effects guys
adding extra locks

810
00:53:01,245 --> 00:53:04,115
and so Marty has like
20 locks he undoes,

811
00:53:04,581 --> 00:53:06,331
and that adds a bit to it.

812
00:53:08,719 --> 00:53:12,699
He's using sort of a Tiki lounge
concept as a reference here.

813
00:53:13,323 --> 00:53:16,482
Marty has this sort of
‘60s bachelor pad, I guess.

