slowed down the sequence.

952
01:03:26,202 --> 01:03:28,162
It was great working
with this layout team

953
01:03:28,505 --> 01:03:30,995
to find really inventive ways
to do the storytelling

954
01:03:31,408 --> 01:03:34,337
and to emphasize certain emotions,
where you put the camera.

955
01:03:34,811 --> 01:03:37,121
And you try and think of it
like a live action film.

956
01:03:37,514 --> 01:03:40,854
You have these miniature sets built
and these performers within that,

957
01:03:41,384 --> 01:03:45,574
and it's all a virtual world, but you do
have cameras and lenses and lights

958
01:03:46,222 --> 01:03:49,322
and there are creative people
working those elements

959
01:03:49,826 --> 01:03:51,576
like you would in a live action film.

960
01:03:51,895 --> 01:03:56,235
So it's a really neat
and challenging process

961
01:03:56,900 --> 01:04:01,240
and there's a lot more to it creatively
than most people imagine, in animation.

962
01:04:18,788 --> 01:04:22,298
There's an entire department that
just constructs all the models for us.

963
01:04:23,259 --> 01:04:26,799
What makes these films interesting
is every film can have its own style,

964
01:04:27,364 --> 01:04:29,614
and we wanted to definitely have
our own style.

965
01:04:29,999 --> 01:04:33,038
Kendall pushed a lot of the design,
you know, so it's very unique.

966
01:04:33,536 --> 01:04:37,286
So in a way we couldn't borrow
a coffee table from the Shrek universe

967
01:04:37,874 --> 01:04:41,794
because it's a different style
of how it's made and graphically.

968
01:04:42,412 --> 01:04:45,631
So, every little thing you see,
every prop, every blade of grass,

969
01:04:46,149 --> 01:04:49,308
everything has been made
from scratch for this movie alone.

970
01:05:11,107 --> 01:05:15,117
We have this Wonderful World song
you've seen in many films,

971
01:05:15,745 --> 01:05:18,174
to contrast what the characters
are going through.

972
01:05:18,581 --> 01:05:22,271
We'd used it for such a long time
we couldn't find anything better

973
01:05:22,852 --> 01:05:24,662
to play with this montage,

974
01:05:24,988 --> 01:05:28,388
which is virtually created
from Rob Koo, I think.

975
01:05:28,925 --> 01:05:32,675
He storyboarded all these characters
kind of walking through

976
01:05:33,263 --> 01:05:37,013
and each one getting picked off
by a different predator later on.

977
01:05:37,600 --> 01:05:40,120
So it was pretty funny.
It just kind of grew from there

978
01:05:40,537 --> 01:05:44,047
and then we added Alex
building his cage,

979
01:05:44,607 --> 01:05:47,417
because he was so afraid
about hurting his friends.

980
01:05:48,812 --> 01:05:51,442
With the foosas
it's very difficult, you know,

981
01:05:51,881 --> 01:05:54,221
‘cause we went back and forth.

982
01:05:54,617 --> 01:05:57,047
Do they talk?
What do they say when they talk?

983
01:05:57,454 --> 01:05:59,474
And for a while they did.

984
01:06:01,324 --> 01:06:04,924
We found that we didn't need them
to communicate so much,

985
01:06:05,495 --> 01:06:06,865
but just to be savage,

986
01:06:07,130 --> 01:06:10,670
and to reflect where Alex
would actually go to,

987
01:06:11,234 --> 01:06:13,984
this non-speaking,

988
01:06:14,437 --> 01:06:17,247
guttural, savage creature.

989
01:06:17,707 --> 01:06:19,167
Little ducky.

990
01:06:19,442 --> 01:06:22,022
We were going to have him say,
"Are you my mommy?" to Marty

991
01:06:22,445 --> 01:06:25,925
before he gets eaten,
but that just went a little too far.

992
01:06:28,985 --> 01:06:31,765
We reveal what Alex was constructing.

993
01:06:32,222 --> 01:06:34,472
The Tsingy,
it's actually in Madagascar.

994
01:06:34,858 --> 01:06:37,928
It's a really unique place
of limestone spires

995
01:06:38,428 --> 01:06:41,417
we thought it would be great
to play out the scene there.

996
01:07:13,696 --> 01:07:17,676
Jada again being the strong female

997
01:07:18,301 --> 01:07:20,551
and she's just great.

998
01:07:20,937 --> 01:07:23,307
l mean, she has this kind of...

999
01:07:23,706 --> 01:07:26,806
When she walks into a room,
her presence is there.

1000
01:07:28,244 --> 01:07:29,854
Jada is very petite in reality

1001
01:07:30,146 --> 01:07:34,336
but she has this great
presence about her.

1002
01:07:45,328 --> 01:07:47,028
Animator had fun again here.

1003
01:07:47,330 --> 01:07:50,549
We always try to give them a lot
of freedom to go crazy with this stuff.

1004
01:07:56,639 --> 01:07:58,509
It's one of those things
that worked out

1005
01:07:58,841 --> 01:08:01,151
with our friends
coming back from Antarctica.

1006
01:08:01,544 --> 01:08:04,004
We wanted to have the boat
come back,

1007
01:08:04,414 --> 01:08:06,194
so they see their opportunity to leave,

1008
01:08:06,516 --> 01:08:09,976
but it was nice to be able to bring
the penguins back at this time.

1009
01:08:26,769 --> 01:08:29,519
Every shot just has ocean
in the background.

1010
01:08:31,040 --> 01:08:33,729
One of these shots
coming up right here

1011
01:08:34,176 --> 01:08:37,277
has 15,000 trees, right here,

1012
01:08:37,779 --> 01:08:40,649
with four million blowing leaves

1013
01:08:41,117 --> 01:08:43,107
that they created
just for that one shot.

1014
01:08:43,453 --> 01:08:47,203
And the effects team was just like,
"We want to do this shot,"

1015
01:08:47,790 --> 01:08:50,010
and we're so grateful to them
for pulling it off.

1016
01:08:53,830 --> 01:08:56,850
That was a line that Tom
just invented on the fly as a joke.

1017
01:08:57,332 --> 01:08:59,522
We never thought
we'd use it at the time,

1018
01:08:59,902 --> 01:09:02,832
and then we were listening to takes
and we said, wait a minute,

1019
01:09:03,305 --> 01:09:05,616
- we should try and blend this in.
- Can we say that?

1020
01:09:06,009 --> 01:09:07,649
Kill them and eat their liver?

1021
01:09:07,944 --> 01:09:10,904
We decided we could say it as long
as we were sure he was joking.

1022
01:09:23,960 --> 01:09:27,590
The skipper is barking off these orders,
and the scene was animated.

1023
01:09:30,099 --> 01:09:31,739
They get the locals to help them.

1024
01:09:32,035 --> 01:09:34,345
That's why that skipper line
was still in there.

1025
01:09:34,737 --> 01:09:37,047
The hearts and minds of the natives.

1026
01:09:37,439 --> 01:09:40,370
But we changed the sequence
and they're no longer part of it.

1027
01:09:43,779 --> 01:09:47,819
These signs really helped us.
You know, it's maybe cheap to do that,

1028
01:09:48,451 --> 01:09:51,911
but we knew which side of the island
was which, in a way.

1029
01:09:52,455 --> 01:09:54,265
It's in our tone still.

1030
01:10:04,333 --> 01:10:08,143
Here it kind of borders on creepy
with all these smiling steaks.

1031
01:10:08,738 --> 01:10:12,078
l remember the sound guys put in
the sound of goats and little children,

1032
01:10:12,608 --> 01:10:16,008
and we were going, wait a second,
this isn't Silence Of The Lambs.

1033
01:10:19,816 --> 01:10:22,916
They were really fun to work with,
these guys. Really creative.

1034
01:10:23,419 --> 01:10:26,229
Chris and Ben did a great job
with the performances here.

1035
01:10:26,689 --> 01:10:29,709
This is a scene though
where we went,

1036
01:10:30,193 --> 01:10:32,473
we changed the dialogue
in subtle ways,

1037
01:10:32,862 --> 01:10:35,382
and Chris at the time
was doing the Oscars,

1038
01:10:35,798 --> 01:10:37,788
and he was really cramped for time.

1039
01:10:38,134 --> 01:10:40,914
And I remember we actually...
He let us come to his hotel

1040
01:10:41,370 --> 01:10:44,120
and we set up a suite
and recorded this stuff.

1041
01:10:44,574 --> 01:10:48,034
And he did a really
brilliant performance.

1042
01:10:48,578 --> 01:10:51,708
But there was a technical problem
with the audio,

1043
01:10:52,215 --> 01:10:55,315
and we had to animate this scene,

1044
01:10:55,818 --> 01:10:58,538
we had to go back in with him
after the Oscars.

1045
01:10:58,988 --> 01:11:01,238
The day after, I think.

1046
01:11:01,624 --> 01:11:04,174
He said everybody else
was calling to congratulate him.

1047
01:11:04,594 --> 01:11:07,464
DreamWorks called to say, hey,
can we get you back in the studio?

1048
01:11:07,930 --> 01:11:10,390
How he was great, you know,
and it's hard for the...

1049
01:11:10,800 --> 01:11:13,490
They have to recreate
their performances, you know,

1050
01:11:13,936 --> 01:11:18,276
and, luckily, our actors were
really patient to the process,

1051
01:11:18,941 --> 01:11:20,371
which can be very difficult

1052
01:11:20,643 --> 01:11:23,513
and sometimes that happens
where you have to redo stuff.

1053
01:11:23,980 --> 01:11:26,230
We see all these
beautiful images on screen

1054
01:11:26,616 --> 01:11:28,836
that the art department
helps us realize.

1055
01:11:29,218 --> 01:11:31,407
But the other side of that equation

1056
01:11:31,788 --> 01:11:34,687
is the work that Philippe Gluckman
and his team do,

1057
01:11:35,158 --> 01:11:39,078
to bring these artistic ideas
to the screen in three-dimension.

1058
01:11:39,695 --> 01:11:42,155
Managing how all the effects look,

1059
01:11:42,565 --> 01:11:46,815
how the surfaces look,
how the light reacts with these objects.

1060
01:11:47,470 --> 01:11:51,280
It's a huge task. Philippe and his team
have just done an incredible job,

1061
01:11:51,874 --> 01:11:55,124
sometimes recreating
almost exactly

1062
01:11:55,645 --> 01:11:58,275
what was conceived

1063
01:11:58,714 --> 01:12:01,174
in the artistic development process.

1064
01:12:01,584 --> 01:12:04,334
And then taking things
to new levels too,

1065
01:12:04,787 --> 01:12:07,367
often in ways
that surprised us sometimes.

1066
01:12:07,790 --> 01:12:10,660
We didn't think that maybe
some things were possible.

1067
01:12:11,127 --> 01:12:14,757
We'd ask Philippe and he'd scratch his
head and say, "Let me think about it,"

1068
01:12:15,331 --> 01:12:17,881
and come back the next day
and say, "Yeah, we can do that."

1069
01:12:19,869 --> 01:12:21,679
Beautiful backgrounds here,

1070
01:12:22,004 --> 01:12:25,224
dark moody lighting
and the plants blowing gently,

1071
01:12:25,741 --> 01:12:28,901
all help contribute to the tone.

1072
01:12:29,412 --> 01:12:32,342
And the animation here,
it isn't as broad and whacky

1073
01:12:32,815 --> 01:12:36,184
as it is in some other scenes
and has a little more subtleties.

1074
01:12:36,419 --> 01:12:38,469
I think the animators did a great job

1075
01:12:39,789 --> 01:12:43,419
of just pulling off
these subtle moments.

1076
01:12:43,993 --> 01:12:45,833
And we launch into action.

1077
01:12:49,699 --> 01:12:52,329
This is another little bit
we had to shorten for time,

1078
01:12:54,136 --> 01:12:56,796
but Marty was pleading
to the foosas not to eat him

1079
01:12:57,240 --> 01:12:58,610
because he had mad cow disease

1080
01:12:58,875 --> 01:13:01,655
and other Chris Rock
kind of standup routine

1081
01:13:02,111 --> 01:13:03,861
as these foosa
were encircling him.

1082
01:13:06,582 --> 01:13:09,012
But it ended up slowing down
the action a little bit.

1083
01:13:23,432 --> 01:13:27,152
Again one of the things we discovered
which was very difficult, whipped cream.

1084
01:13:27,737 --> 01:13:29,437
Let that be a lesson to everyone.

1085
01:13:33,809 --> 01:13:35,389
Massive undertaking again here.

1086
01:13:35,678 --> 01:13:38,338
All these individual foosa
have to be animated by hand.

1087
01:13:38,781 --> 01:13:42,351
You can't tell the computer to move
them around. It doesn't look natural.

1088
01:13:42,919 --> 01:13:44,289
The Whac-a-Mole gag.

1089
01:13:57,833 --> 01:14:01,173
An amazing roar designed
by the sound effects folks.

1090
01:14:01,704 --> 01:14:04,693
It was very hard to get a real lion's
roar, we've discovered,

1091
01:14:05,174 --> 01:14:07,664
because they don't really roar
for very long.

1092
01:14:08,077 --> 01:14:10,187
They do really short little blasts.

1093
01:14:10,546 --> 01:14:12,386
So the sound guys
had to create one for us.

1094
01:14:17,119 --> 01:14:20,398
You know, one of the things
that made Alex savage visually,

1095
01:14:20,923 --> 01:14:23,112
his teeth used to turn sharp.

1096
01:14:23,492 --> 01:14:25,332
We had this second set of teeth
for him.

1097
01:14:25,661 --> 01:14:28,501
But it really, really looked like Alien.

1098
01:14:28,965 --> 01:14:31,015
So we decided not to use
those kind of teeth

1099
01:14:31,367 --> 01:14:33,097
and keep him with his normal ones.

1100
01:14:33,402 --> 01:14:35,132
Usually teeth don't change anyway.

1101
01:15:01,297 --> 01:15:03,757
You know, in the end,
just the sound editing,

1102
01:15:04,166 --> 01:15:07,096
what H and those guys did,

1103
01:15:07,570 --> 01:15:10,670
it's really amazing technically
how this all works.

1104
01:15:11,173 --> 01:15:13,603
With all these guys
screaming on top of each other,

1105
01:15:14,010 --> 01:15:16,350
and, you know, they're all
recorded separately

1106
01:15:16,746 --> 01:15:19,086
and it takes a large amount
of patience in editing

1107
01:15:19,482 --> 01:15:22,552
to string all these vocal
performances together

1108
01:15:23,052 --> 01:15:26,512
and make it sound like everyone's
working with each other.

1109
01:15:27,056 --> 01:15:31,156
A little funny nunchucks bit
that the animator put in.

1110
01:15:31,794 --> 01:15:34,314
Really shows off what we can
do with the characters

1111
01:15:34,730 --> 01:15:37,190
and how we can move them
.
In a sequence.

1112
01:15:37,600 --> 01:15:41,520
Our character TD's or technical
directors are the ones that set these up

1113
01:15:42,138 --> 01:15:45,478
so that they can be sort of
pushed and pulled to such extremes.

1114
01:15:46,008 --> 01:15:48,407
Robyn, Alain,
and the others did a great job,

1115
01:15:48,811 --> 01:15:50,981
giving the animators
the handles they needed

1116
01:15:51,347 --> 01:15:53,777
to do this kind of
over the top animation.

1117
01:15:56,886 --> 01:16:01,276
And Rex Grignon was fantastic
as an animation supervisor

1118
01:16:01,957 --> 01:16:05,587
who really pushed the animators
and helped set the tone

1119
01:16:06,162 --> 01:16:08,032
of the style of animation
we were after.

1120
01:16:08,364 --> 01:16:10,174
You can't thank those guys enough.

1121
01:16:10,499 --> 01:16:12,429
You never can,
because there's so many.

1122
01:16:12,768 --> 01:16:15,758
There's probably 50 animators.
that contributed to this film,

1123
01:16:16,238 --> 01:16:17,758
whose work is seamless.

1124
01:16:18,040 --> 01:16:19,107
Every animator has his own shot,

1125
01:16:19,108 --> 01:16:19,778
Every animator has his own shot,

1126
01:16:19,942 --> 01:16:22,552
and they'd run right next
to each other.

1127
01:16:22,978 --> 01:16:26,018
So it's amazing how continuous
it all feels afterwards.

1128
01:16:40,362 --> 01:16:43,792
We decided Alex could eat fish,
since fish don't talk in our movie.

1129
01:16:44,333 --> 01:16:46,522
- They're not.
- You can eat all the fish you want.

1130
01:16:46,902 --> 01:16:48,512
Because a lion really can't...

1131
01:16:48,804 --> 01:16:51,904
it's impossible for them to really
live off vegetables and fruit.

1132
01:16:52,408 --> 01:16:53,868
Have to have protein some way,

1133
01:16:54,143 --> 01:16:57,833
so fish was our
serendipitous solution for that.

1134
01:16:59,115 --> 01:17:03,425
Marty actually had
teeth marks on his butt

1135
01:17:04,086 --> 01:17:05,546
from where he was bitten.

1136
01:17:07,022 --> 01:17:10,562
In the computer it never looked right.
It always looked really gruesome,

1137
01:17:11,127 --> 01:17:13,437
with little blood specks
or a little pink thing.

1138
01:17:13,829 --> 01:17:14,938
It didn't look right.

1139
01:17:15,164 --> 01:17:19,443
The ultimate solution they came up with
was a Band-Aid, which works out great.

1140
01:17:21,303 --> 01:17:25,523
The story artists bring a huge
amount of creativity to the table.

1141
01:17:26,175 --> 01:17:30,335
They don't just get the script and draw
what's on the page necessarily.

1142
01:17:30,980 --> 01:17:33,120
They use that as a guide.

1143
01:17:33,482 --> 01:17:37,112
Catherine Rader and Rob Koo
are our two lead story artists

1144
01:17:37,686 --> 01:17:40,375
and contributed so much
original material.

1145
01:17:40,823 --> 01:17:42,633
Much of what you see on-screen

1146
01:17:42,958 --> 01:17:45,567
was actually never
in the original script sometimes.

1147
01:17:45,995 --> 01:17:49,915
And Rob and Catherine are very much
filmmakers in their own right

1148
01:17:50,533 --> 01:17:53,813
as they take these script pages,
just the written word,

1149
01:17:54,336 --> 01:17:58,376
and turn it into cinema,
along with their team of story artists.

1150
01:17:59,008 --> 01:18:03,168
And the first performance
is in the drawings as well.

1151
01:18:05,381 --> 01:18:07,021
So that's how you visualize this,

1152
01:18:07,316 --> 01:18:11,186
and from there everyone else
is inspired by the storyboard drawings.

1153
