01:19:54,123 --> 01:19:56,343
As Eric said, that's why
we have two directors.

1181
01:19:56,725 --> 01:19:59,715
We could each work
on separate teams.

1182
01:20:00,195 --> 01:20:04,005
But Eric and I could always
get together, and with Mireille

1183
01:20:04,600 --> 01:20:07,410
and kind of know
the film we wanted to make.

1184
01:20:07,870 --> 01:20:10,910
So it was easy for us to split up
and divide and conquer in that way.

1185
01:20:11,407 --> 01:20:14,807
And it sort of worked that way
with producers as well.

1186
01:20:15,344 --> 01:20:17,594
Mireille would often be in one location

1187
01:20:17,980 --> 01:20:19,759
and the co-producer
Teresa Cheng

1188
01:20:20,082 --> 01:20:23,772
would be up at the production facility
in Northern California,

1189
01:20:25,954 --> 01:20:29,233
managing the production
and all the folks

1190
01:20:29,758 --> 01:20:32,657
and the schedules
that were necessary.

1191
01:20:33,128 --> 01:20:35,027
We did it in two locations.

1192
01:20:35,364 --> 01:20:38,174
We have a DreamWorks campus
in Glendale, California,

1193
01:20:38,634 --> 01:20:41,324
and then one
in Redwood City, California,

1194
01:20:41,770 --> 01:20:44,170
about an hour plane ride apart,

1195
01:20:45,841 --> 01:20:48,831
and a lot of high end technology
and video conferencing systems

1196
01:20:49,311 --> 01:20:52,710
that allowed us to bridge
that gap a little bit.

1197
01:20:54,049 --> 01:20:56,949
Often Tom and ! would find ourselves
in different locations,

1198
01:20:57,419 --> 01:20:59,499
or Mireille and Teresa would be.

1199
01:20:59,855 --> 01:21:02,075
Which was probably
in a total of, like,

1200
01:21:02,458 --> 01:21:05,498
a four-year process,
four-and-a-half-year process

1201
01:21:05,994 --> 01:21:08,044
of working on this film,
the last third of it

1202
01:21:08,397 --> 01:21:10,977
is actually in production
with all the animators.

1203
01:21:11,400 --> 01:21:14,210
All these people come aboard

1204
01:21:14,670 --> 01:21:16,420
and help create this thing.

1205
01:21:16,739 --> 01:21:19,839
So it takes a long time
to do one of these things.

1206
01:21:21,643 --> 01:21:23,723
But when you see it all done,

1207
01:21:24,079 --> 01:21:28,058
and the work everyone else has done,
it's really fantastic to see.

1208
01:21:28,684 --> 01:21:31,904
Every one of these names that
you're seeing is actually someone

1209
01:21:32,421 --> 01:21:35,701
who contributed a great deal of time
and creative energy on the film,

1210
01:21:36,225 --> 01:21:39,215
so that's a lot of them, yeah.

1211
01:21:39,695 --> 01:21:42,974
And any one of them is
a tremendous artist in their own right

1212
01:21:43,499 --> 01:21:45,339
who could go out
and do beautiful work

1213
01:21:45,667 --> 01:21:48,797
without Tom and myself
telling them what to do.

1214
01:21:49,304 --> 01:21:52,174
Our job really is
what the name says,

1215
01:21:52,641 --> 01:21:56,271
direct people
all in the same direction,

1216
01:21:56,845 --> 01:21:59,365
so that everybody's
telling the same story.

1217
01:21:59,782 --> 01:22:03,412
We're caretakers
of the story in that sense,

1218
01:22:05,387 --> 01:22:09,487
to make sure all this great creative
work is servicing that main idea.

1219
01:22:10,125 --> 01:22:12,815
Ultimately it doesn't matter
how many polygons you have

1220
01:22:13,262 --> 01:22:16,602
or how many people are in the crowd
or how beautiful the images are,

1221
01:22:17,132 --> 01:22:20,232
if you don't have a story behind it all
that people care about

1222
01:22:20,736 --> 01:22:22,906
and the characters that people love

1223
01:22:23,272 --> 01:22:25,852
and care about what's
going to happen to them next.

1224
01:22:26,275 --> 01:22:29,205
We get to feature some
of the great score work

1225
01:22:29,678 --> 01:22:32,488
that Hans Zimmer and his team
did here in these credits too.

1226
01:22:32,948 --> 01:22:35,168
It was great to bring
some of that music back in.

1227
01:22:35,551 --> 01:22:39,361
This is a great piece.
A lot of it underscores the film,

1228
01:22:39,955 --> 01:22:42,825
but it's nice to hear it
just clean like this.

1229
01:22:43,292 --> 01:22:45,812
This is when they were
escaping from the zoo.

1230
01:22:47,362 --> 01:22:51,172
Hans was trying to do
New York-sounding material.

1231
01:22:51,767 --> 01:22:54,017
Looking at Gershwin,
trying to do his own version,

1232
01:22:54,403 --> 01:22:56,303
and then finally he said,
"What am I doing?

1233
01:22:56,638 --> 01:22:59,327
Anything I do will just be
a cheap imitation of Gershwin.

1234
01:22:59,775 --> 01:23:02,405
I'm going to come up with my
own sound for New York City."

1235
01:23:02,845 --> 01:23:05,155
When he played this for us,
it just gave us chills.

1236
01:23:05,547 --> 01:23:07,156
We thought it was a great piece,

1237
01:23:07,449 --> 01:23:10,438
a great way to underscore,
quite literally, what they're doing

1238
01:23:10,919 --> 01:23:13,439
when they're escaping
in the streets of Manhattan.

1239
01:23:27,269 --> 01:23:31,489
I think there's a montage
of penguins music

1240
01:23:32,140 --> 01:23:33,660
.
coming up soon.

1241
01:23:33,942 --> 01:23:37,862
That was fun to work with too,
to find that tone that sort of...

1242
01:23:38,480 --> 01:23:41,000
These guys have this
black and white mentality,

1243
01:23:41,416 --> 01:23:44,346
this sort of '50s sensibility.

1244
01:23:44,820 --> 01:23:47,719
And to find music that
kind of helped sell that...

1245
01:23:49,625 --> 01:23:52,725
Originally we had crime jazz,
which had a lot of bongos in it,

1246
01:23:53,228 --> 01:23:57,618
and so they latched onto that
kind of retro, detective music

1247
01:23:58,300 --> 01:24:00,760
and added their own bit to it.

1248
01:24:01,169 --> 01:24:02,309
A lot of people.

1249
01:24:02,538 --> 01:24:04,617
A lot of people,
doing a lot of things.

1250
01:24:06,375 --> 01:24:08,015
Here's some more.

1251
01:24:09,044 --> 01:24:12,504
You do these things on computers,
but there's so much support for that,

1252
01:24:13,048 --> 01:24:14,888
and these guys don't get,
you know...

1253
01:24:15,217 --> 01:24:19,607
They invent ways to do new things
and make it

1254
01:24:20,289 --> 01:24:24,129
so the art of computer animation
can just keep expanding.

1255
01:24:24,726 --> 01:24:27,596
Much of the software we use
is all written in-house

1256
01:24:28,063 --> 01:24:31,253
and maintained by computer artists

1257
01:24:31,767 --> 01:24:33,937
and programmers in-house,

1258
01:24:34,303 --> 01:24:38,613
which makes it possible
for us to do things

1259
01:24:39,274 --> 01:24:40,974
that frankly would be impossible

1260
01:24:41,276 --> 01:24:43,616
if we had to depend upon
off-the-shelf software.

1261
01:24:44,012 --> 01:24:45,532
So a lot of those names
you see here

1262
01:24:45,814 --> 01:24:47,984
are helping us achieve
those sorts of things.

1263
01:24:48,350 --> 01:24:51,980
Helping the departments
communicate with one another.

1264
01:24:53,288 --> 01:24:55,748
It's all about the pipeline
in something like this.

1265
01:24:56,158 --> 01:24:58,438
The last thing you want
is to have teams of people

1266
01:24:58,827 --> 01:25:01,817
sitting, waiting
for inventory to work on.

1267
01:25:02,297 --> 01:25:05,286
So it's a monumental task
to keep that flowing

1268
01:25:05,767 --> 01:25:07,987
and a lot of these people
help with that as well.

1269
01:25:43,271 --> 01:25:46,731
Here we come with our final
little goodbye from Gloria.

1270
01:25:48,276 --> 01:25:51,086
Well, it's been a lot of fun.
Hope you guys enjoyed it.

